# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charles-ragon-de-bange
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] 78/10/31** were field guns produced and used by Poland during World War II and Finland during the Continuation War.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] After the defeat of the Central Powers during World War I the Allies agreed to reconstitute the country of Poland from the territory which had been partitioned by the German Empire, Austro-Hungarian Empire, and Russian Empire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The new armed forces of the Second Polish Republic inherited a mix of German, Russian and Austro-Hungarian weapons from its former occupiers.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Poland also received French technical assistance and weapons to rebuild its armed forces after World War I.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Large numbers of Russian weapons were also captured during the Polish-Soviet War when the Red Army was defeated after the Battle of Warsaw in 1920.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] 78/10/31 were a combination of the gun barrels from the Canon de 120 mm L mle 1878 field guns supplied by France and the carriages of the Russian 152 mm M1909 and 152 mm M1910 howitzers.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The name of the guns signifies the dates of manufacture for each of the components used.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] 78 indicated the barrel was from 1878, 09 and 10 indicated the carriages came from either the M1909 and M1910, and 31 indicated the design was completed and construction began in 1931.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The mle 1878 was a breech loaded gun with a de Bange obturator and used separate loading bagged charges and projectiles.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] It had a box trail carriage, no gun shield, two wooden-spoked steel-rimmed wheels, an unsprung axle, and no recoil mechanism.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The mle 1878 was lighter than its heavier brother the Canon de 155 mm L mle 1877.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] It had roughly the same range and rate of fire as the Canon 155 mm L mle 1877, but it fired a lighter projectile.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The 120 mm L mle 1878 was classified as a *siege et de place* (stationary siege gun) in France's Séré de Rivières system of fortifications.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] In line with this mission, the carriage was tall because it was expected that its barrel would overhang a parapet and use its range to provide long-range, low-angle counter-battery fire against enemy artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Although an elderly weapon at the time of World War I, it was available in large numbers and its heavy projectile and long-range made it a useful weapon and many were still in use during World War II.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] An early drawback of the gun was that it required considerable time to prepare a firing platform made of concrete or timbers before use.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] An external recoil cylinder was then bolted to the platform and connected to an eyelet on the bottom of the gun carriage.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Without it, the gun had no recoil mechanism and when fired the gun rolled back onto a set of ramps behind the wheels and then slid back into position.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Since it lacked a recoil mechanism it had to be levered into position and re-aimed after every shot, which was strenuous, time-consuming, and limited its rate of fire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The height of the gun also limited the rate of fire since a gun crew needed to lift an 18.9 kg (42 lb) projectile to shoulder height.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Another drawback of the mle 1878 was since its carriage was tall and narrow it was top-heavy and not designed to be mobile.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] It was found it had a tendency to sink in on soft ground and since it was designed to be pulled at low speed by a horse team its wooden-spoked steel-rimmed wheels and axle were too fragile to be towed at high speed by motor traction.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] An early modification to make the guns suitable for field use was the fitting of Bonagente grousers to the wheels to improve balance and reduce ground pressure on soft ground.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] A bonus was they slowed recoil and didn't require extensive site preparation to bring the guns into action.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] These factors made the mle 1878 unsuitable for anything other than static defense during World War II.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The M1909 and M1910 were ordered by the Imperial Russian Army in the wake of the Russian Empire's defeat during the Russo-Japanese War.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The Russian Army was in the process of re-equipping with new weapons and at the time the Russian Armed Forces were heavily reliant upon French and German designs.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The M1909 and M1910 were designed by the French company Schneider-Creusot and were produced in large numbers under license at the Putilov and Perm factories in Russia.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The heavier M1909 was designated a *kryepostnaya gaubitsa* (fortress howitzer) while the lighter M1910 was designated a *polevaya gaubitsa* (field howitzer).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The two howitzers had similar performance but differed in the arrangement of their recoil mechanisms and gun shields.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The M1909/1910 were conventional designs for their time.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] They had a box trail carriage with wooden-spoked steel-rimmed wheels, a gun shield to protect the crew, and a hydro-pneumatic recoil system mounted under the barrel.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] They had an interrupted screw breech with separate loading ammunition; the shell being loaded first followed by bagged charges in a brass cartridge case.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The carriage had a hollow center section to allow the barrel to elevate from -3° to 45° and there was an integral loading tray near the breech.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] When World War I broke out the M1910 was the most modern howitzer design that France had so its carriage and recoil system were used on the Canon de 105 mle 1913, 107 mm gun M1910, Canon de 155 C mle 1917, and Obusier de 120 mm mle 15TR produced by Schneider-Creusot.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The advantage of the M1909/1910 over the mle 1878 was that its recoil mechanism allowed it to achieve a higher rate of fire because it took less time to re-aim.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Also since the M1909/1910 was shorter than the mle 1878 and had an integral loading tray it was faster to load.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The carriage of the M1909/1910 was also more durable than the mle 1878 carriage and that gave it better mobility.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] A disadvantage of the M1909/1910 was that it had a shorter range than the mle 1878 so it was vulnerable to counter-battery fire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] In 1931 the Starachowice Works began converting the barrels and carriages to create the 120 mm Armata wz.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] It is estimated that 43 guns were modified at the Starachowice Works and delivered to the Polish Army.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] An advantage of the M1909/1910 was that the recoil mechanism was an integral part of the carriage and the barrel could be removed and transported on a separate wagon or could be pulled to the rear and fastened to the carriage to ease transport.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] This feature meant the carriage and recoil mechanism could be modified to accept longer or shorter barrels as well as barrels of greater diameter.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] To mate the mle 1878 barrel to the M1909/1910 carriage the barrel was rotated 180 degrees so that the breech opened to the right instead of the left.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The recoil mechanism also needed to be balanced to accommodate the new longer barrel.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The chamber was also enlarged and strengthened to accept up to six propellant charges and the de Bange breech was modified to use modern primers.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The carriage could either retain its original wooden-spoked steel-rimmed wheels for horse traction or it could be modified to use pneumatic tires and a sprung axle to allow for motor traction.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Pneumatic tires and a sprung axle gave better traction on soft ground as well as increasing towing speed.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] 78/09/31 the M1909/1910's carriage and recoil mechanism were used to modernize the Canon de 155 mm L mle 1877 by placing the barrels from that gun on the M1910 carriage to produce the Canon de 155 L modèle 1877/14, Canon de 155 L modèle 1917 and Canon de 155 L modèle 1918 during World War I.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] By using the M1909/1910 carriage both the French and Polish were able to modernize existing 120 mm and 155 mm mle 1878 barrels to produce more mobile and long-ranged artillery pieces that utilized the large stockpiles of ammunition available for both types.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] In Polish service, the Cannon de 120 mm L mle 1878 was given the designation *armata wz.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] 1878.* The first Polish unit to use the wz.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] 1878 was General Józef Haller's *Blue Army* that was created in France in 1917.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] 1878's and were issued to two Heavy Artillery Regiments with four detachments.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] When World War I ended the Blue Army returned to Poland with their guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] After World War I Poland received more wz.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] 1878's and in 1931 54 guns were in Poland's inventory.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Some had been modernized with a barrel that had been relined to use constant rifling instead of progressive rifling.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The modified guns were designated wz.1878/16 in Polish Service.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] In Polish service, a number of different styles of wheels were used to improve the mobility of the guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Some retained wooden-spoked steel-rimmed wheels for horse traction while others were given pneumatic tires, sprung axles, and were towed by Citroën-Kegresse P14 or C4P half-track artillery tractors.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] There were an additional 4 wz.1878/09/31 guns in reserve which lacked full equipment for a total of 42 guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] There were also 13 unconverted wz.1878 barrels in reserve.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] In 1939 there were three Heavy Artillery Detachments with 12 guns each that were held in reserve.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Of these three the 46th and 47th Heavy Artillery Detachment were horse-drawn while the 6th Heavy Artillery Detachment was motorized.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] All were active in the defense of Poland and they faced both German and Soviet units.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] After the Polish Campaign 24 of the surviving guns were sold to Finland.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Finland bought 24 guns and 46,200 rounds of ammunition from Germany in the autumn of 1940.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] The guns arrived in two shipments: 13 guns arrived on the *Inga* on the 2nd of October 1940 and the remaining 11 guns arrived on the *Widor* on the 9th of October 1940.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] In Finnish service, the unmodified Canon de 120 mm L mle 1878 was given the designation *120 K/78* and the new guns from Poland were given the designation *120 K/78-31.* Since the 120 K/78 was already in service there was an adequate supply of ammunition for both.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] During the Continuation War, both guns were issued to four heavy artillery battalions.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] They gained a reputation of being durable and good quality artillery pieces, but the new primer system proved troublesome and the recoil system wasn't always reliable in cold weather.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/09-31] Two of the guns were lost during 1944 and After World War 2 the remaining guns were placed in reserve until they were retired during the 1960s.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The **8×50mmR Lebel** (8mm Lebel) (designated as the **8 × 51 R Lebel** by the C.I.P.) rifle cartridge was the first smokeless powder cartridge to be made and adopted by any country.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11×59mmR Gras black powder cartridge, the smokeless 8mm Lebel cartridge started a revolution in military rifle ammunition.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Standard 8mm Lebel military ammunition was also the first rifle ammunition to feature a spitzer boat tail bullet (*balle* D), which was adopted in 1898.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The long-range ballistic performance of the 8mm Lebel bullet itself was exceptional for its time.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] For use in the magazine tube-fed early Lebel rifle, the 8 mm case was designed to protect against accidental percussion inside the tube magazine by a circular groove around the primer cup which caught the tip of the following pointed bullet.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] However, the shape of its rimmed bottle-necked case, having been designed for the Lebel rifle's tube magazine, also precluded truly efficient vertical stacking inside a vertical magazine.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The bolt thrust of the 8mm Lebel is relatively high compared to many other service rounds used in the early 20th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Although it was once revolutionary, the 8mm Lebel was declared obsolete after World War I and was soon after replaced with the 7.5×54mm French round.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] There were two historical commercially available 8mm Lebel cartridges: one for the Lebel Model 1886 rifle, and one for the Modèle 1892 revolver.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] They are two entirely different cartridges and are not interchangeable.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The term "8mm Lebel" for the French Mle 1892 revolver ammunition, is only applied outside France for commercial reasons and has nothing to do with the Lebel rifle.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] However, the term "8mm Lebel", used to identify a rifle cartridge, is widely recognized to distinguish the French rifle cartridge from other 8 mm rifle cartridges, such as the 8×50mmR Mannlicher cartridge used by Austria-Hungary and its successor states.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The cartridge for the tube-fed long arm was originally loaded with a 15.0 g (232 grains) cupro-nickel-jacketed, lead-cored, flat-nosed, wadcutter-style bullet, called "*balle M*", which had been designed by Lieutenant Colonel Nicolas Lebel.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The flat point (flat nose or tip) of this bullet had been designed to be safe inside the newly commissioned rifle's tube magazine.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] It was propelled by the first practical smokeless, nitrocellulose-based powder (*Poudre B*), as developed by Paul Vieille in 1884.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The ballistic performance and range of *balle M* with the new propellant eclipsed all the previous military ammunitions in existence at the time (1886).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] This *balle M* was replaced in 1898 by a new design, a 12.8 g (198 grains) 90/10 bronze mono-metal, pointed (spitzer) boat-tail bullet called "*balle D*", which provided a flatter trajectory and improved long-range performance.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Designed at the Atelier de Puteaux (APX) by Captain Georges Desaleux, the *balle D* was the first pointed *and* boat-tailed bullet to be placed into service by any military.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Later on in 1912, the round was improved into the *balle D am* ("am" stands for "*amorçage modifié*" or "modified primer"), done by crimping the primer in more deeply to prevent primer expulsions when fired in machine guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] This ammunition was in near-universal service during World War I (1914–1918) in all Lebel-caliber weapons.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The *balle D am* ammunition was followed in 1932 by *balle N* ammunition, which featured a lead-cored, cupro-nickel-over-steel-jacketed, pointed boat-tail bullet weighing 15.0 g (232 grains).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] It was thicker (8.3 mm instead of 8.17) and was held into a case that had a slightly larger neck diameter than that for the older *balle D am* ammunition.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The new *balle N* was again heavier than the *balle D am*, and had been designed to improve the long-range performance of the issued Hotchkiss machine guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Rechambering practically all French Lebel-caliber rifles and carbines to use the "N"-type ammunition was carried out during the 1930s.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] A *balle T* (tracer ammunition) and *balle P* armor-piercing rounds were also produced, along with blank and reduced charge cartridges.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] In order to safely accommodate pointed (spitzer) bullets inside the Lebel rifle magazine, a circular groove was machined around each primer cup at the case base on both *balle D am* and *balle N* ammunitions.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The role of that circular groove is to receive the pointed bullet tip of the following round loaded inside the tube magazine, and keep it *at the side* of the case base of the previous cartridge, so the tip does not easily slide to the base center where the primer is located.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The tapered form of the case itself did help too to keep pointed tips away from the primer cup of a round in front of another in the tube.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Furthermore, all *balle D* and *balle M* French military ammunitions featured *convex primer covers* which are crimped in over the primer itself.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Those small covers are not noticeable, but do provide a second effective protection against accidental primer percussion inside the Lebel's tube magazine.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Wartime experiences (1914–1918) involving hundreds of millions of Lebel rounds fired in combat have entirely confirmed the effectiveness of these protections.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] While revolutionary for its time in terms of ballistic performance, the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge had its drawbacks.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11mm Gras rifle cartridge case, it was an odd design, with a thick rim and a rapid double taper.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] This made it more difficult to feed from standard magazine firearms such as the Berthier rifles and the Chauchat machine guns, and is the reason for the distinct curvature in the magazines of those firearms.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The Lebel rifle from which it was fired was also rather outdated by the time *balle D*, let alone the *balle N*, came along.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] A *balle N* round can only be fired from Lebel or Berthier rifles, if the chamber has been reamed to accept the larger neck of the N-type cartridge.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Such weapons are stamped *N* on top of the barrel, just in front of the receiver and behind the rear sight.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The *balle N* ammunition is identifiable by the fact that the bullet, while pointed like the solid-brass *balle D*, is lead-cored and jacketed with soft steel.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] While newly manufactured 8×50mmR Lebel ammunition has become available in the U.S., reloadable cartridge cases can also be produced by reforming .348 Winchester brass.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The 8mm Lebel round produced by Prvi Partizan is of excellent quality and replicates the performance of the original round.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] However, Privi Partizan's *older style* brass cases lack the circular groove around the primer cup, so reloaders use round-nosed or flat-nosed bullets when producing handloads for the tube-magazine Lebel rifles with these cases.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] The older Privi Partizan cases loaded with spire point bullets should only be fired single shot.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] More recently, Privi Partizan manufactured Lebel ammunition with spitzer bullets do incorporate the circular groove at the base, and are safe when stacked in the box-magazine of Berthier rifles and the tubular magazine of Lebel rifles.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] Newer cases with circular groove follow the *balle D* specifications, and shooters may use the magazine for loading.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] 1929 (7.5 French) cartridge was introduced.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/8mm-lebel] This made the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge obsolete, but due to post-World War I financial constraints and political neglect, it was not introduced as a rifle cartridge until the adoption, just before World War II, of the MAS-36 rifle.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The purpose of ammunition is to project a force against a selected target to have an effect (usually, but not always, lethal).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] An example of ammunition is the firearm cartridge, which includes all components required to deliver the weapon's effect in a single package.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Until the 20th century, black powder was the most common propellant used, but it has now been replaced in nearly all cases by modern compounds.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Ammunition comes in a wide range of sizes and types and is often designed to work only with specific weapon systems.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] However, there are internationally recognized standards for certain ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) that enable their use across different weapons and by different users.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] There are also specific types of ammunition that are designed to have a specialized effect on a target, such as armor-piercing shells and tracer ammunition, used only in certain circumstances.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Ammunition is commonly labeled or colored in a specific manner to assist in its identification and to prevent the wrong ammunition types from being used accidentally or inappropriately.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The term *ammunition* dates back to the mid-17th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The word comes from the French *la munition*, for the material used for war.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] *Ammunition* and *munition* are often used interchangeably, although *munition* now usually refers to the actual weapons system with the ammunition required to operate it.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] In some languages other than English ammunition is still referred to as munition, such as: Dutch ("*munitie*"), French ("*munitions*"), German ("*Munition*"), Italian ("*munizione*") and Portuguese ("*munição*").
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Ammunition design has evolved throughout history as different weapons have been developed and different effects required.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Historically, ammunition was of relatively simple design and build (e.g., sling-shot, stones hurled by catapults), but as weapon designs developed (e.g., rifling) and became more refined, the need for more specialized ammunition increased.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Modern ammunition can vary significantly in quality but is usually manufactured to very high standards.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] For example, ammunition for hunting can be designed to expand inside a target, maximizing the damage inflicted by one round.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Anti-personnel shells are designed to fragment into many pieces and can affect a large area.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Armor-piercing rounds are specially hardened to penetrate armor, while smoke ammunition creates a fog that screens people from view.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] More generic ammunition (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) can often be modified slightly to achieve a more specific effect (e.g., tracer, incendiary), whilst larger explosive rounds can be altered by using different fuzes.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The term *fuze* refers to the detonator of an explosive round or shell.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The spelling is different in British English and American English (fuse/fuze respectively), and they are unrelated to a fuse (electrical).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] A fuse was earlier used to ignite the propellant (e.g., such as on a firework) until the advent of more reliable systems, such as the primer or igniter that is used in most modern ammunition.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The fuze of a weapon can be used to alter how the ammunition works.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] These allow a single ammunition type to be altered to suit the situation it is required for.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] There are many fuze designs, ranging from simple mechanical to complex radar- and barometric-based systems.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Fuzes are typically armed by the acceleration force of firing the projectile and are armed several meters after clearing the weapon's bore.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] This helps to ensure the ammunition is safer to handle when loading into the weapon and reduces the chance of the detonator firing before the ammunition has cleared the weapon.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The propellant is the component of ammunition that is activated inside the weapon and provides the kinetic energy required to move the projectile from the weapon to the target.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] In recent years, compressed gas, magnetic energy, and electrical energy have been used as propellants.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Until the 20th century, gunpowder was the most common propellant in ammunition.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] However, it has since been replaced by a wide range of fast-burning compounds that are more reliable and efficient.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The propellant charge is distinct from the projectile charge, which is activated by the fuze, which causes the ammunition effect (e.g., the exploding of an artillery round).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The cartridge is the container that holds the projectile and propellant.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Not all ammunition types have a cartridge case.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] In its place, a wide range of materials can be used to contain the explosives and parts.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] With some large weapons, the ammunition components are stored separately until loaded into the weapon system for firing.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] With small arms, caseless ammunition can reduce the weight and cost of ammunition and simplify the firing process, increasing the firing rate, but the technology is still maturing and has functional issues.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The projectile is the part of the ammunition that leaves the weapon and affects the target.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] This effect is usually either kinetic (e.g., as with a standard bullet) or explosive.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] An ammunition dump is a military facility for storing live ammunition and explosives to be distributed and used at a later date.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Such a storage facility is extremely hazardous, with a high risk of accidents during unloading, packing, and transferring the ammunition.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] In the event of a fire or explosion, the site and its surrounding area are immediately evacuated, and the stored ammunition is left to detonate completely, with limited firefighting attempts from a safe distance.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] In large facilities, there may be a flooding system to extinguish a fire or prevent an explosion automatically.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Typically, an ammunition dump will have a large buffer zone surrounding it to avoid casualties in the event of an accident.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] There will also be perimeter security measures in place to prevent unauthorized personnel from accessing the area and to guard against potential threats from enemy forces.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] A magazine is a place where a quantity of ammunition or other explosive material is stored temporarily before being used.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The term may be used for a facility that stores large quantities of ammunition, although this is normally referred to as an ammunition dump.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Magazines are typically located in the field for quick access when engaging the enemy.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The ammunition storage area on a warship is referred to as the "ship's magazine".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] On a smaller scale, magazine is also the name given to the ammunition storage and feeding device of a repeating firearm.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Gunpowder must be stored in a dry place (stable room temperature) to keep it usable for at least 10 years.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] It is also recommended to avoid hot places, because friction or heat might ignite a spark and cause an explosion.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The standard weapon of a modern soldier is an assault rifle, which, like other small arms, uses cartridge ammunition sized for the weapon.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Ammunition is carried on the person in box magazines specific to the weapon, ammunition boxes, pouches, or bandoliers.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The amount of ammunition carried depends on the soldier's strength, the expected action required, and the ammunition's ability to move through the logistical chain to replenish the supply.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] A soldier may also carry a smaller amount of specialized ammunition for heavier weapons, such as machine guns and mortars, thereby spreading the burden of squad weapons among many people.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Too little ammunition threatens the mission, while too much limits the soldier's mobility and also threatens the mission.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] A shell is a payload-carrying projectile which, as opposed to a shot, contains explosives or other fillings, in use since the 19th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Artillery shells are ammunition that is designed to be fired from artillery, which has an effect over long distances, usually indirectly (i.e., out of sight of the target).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] There are many different types of artillery ammunition, but they are usually high-explosive and designed to shatter into fragments on impact to maximize damage.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The fuze on an artillery shell can alter how it explodes or behaves, giving it a more specialized effect.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Common types of artillery ammunition include high explosive, smoke, illumination, and practice rounds.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Some artillery rounds are designed as cluster munitions.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Artillery ammunition will almost always include a projectile (the only exception being demonstration or blank rounds), fuze, and propellant of some form.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] When a cartridge case is not used, another method of containing the propellant bags is used, usually in a breech-loading weapon; see Breechloader.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Tank ammunition was developed in World War I as tanks first appeared on the battlefield.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The development of shaped charges has had a significant impact on anti-tank ammunition design, now common in both tank-fired ammunition and in anti-tank missiles, including anti-tank guided missiles.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Naval weapons were originally the same as many land-based weapons, but the ammunition was designed for specific use, such as a solid shot designed to hole an enemy ship and chain-shot to cut rigging and sails.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Modern naval engagements have occurred over far longer distances than historic battles, so as ship armor has increased in strength and thickness, the ammunition to defeat it has also changed.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Naval ammunition is now designed to reach very high velocities (to improve its armor-piercing abilities) and may have specialized fuzes to defeat specific types of vessels.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] However, due to the extended ranges at which modern naval combat may occur, guided missiles have largely supplanted guns and shells.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] With every successive improvement in military arms, a corresponding change has occurred in the method of supplying ammunition in the required quantities.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] As soon as projectiles were required (such as javelins and arrows), there needed to be a method of replenishment.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] When non-specialized, interchangeable, or recoverable ammunition was used (e.g., arrows), it was possible to pick up spent arrows (both friendly and enemy) and reuse them.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] However, with the advent of explosive or non-recoverable ammunition, this was no longer possible, and new ammunition supplies would be needed.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The weight of ammunition required, particularly for artillery shells, can be considerable, necessitating extra time to replenish supplies.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] In modern times, there has been an increase in the standardization of many ammunition types among allies (e.g., the NATO Standardization Agreement) that has enabled the sharing of ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] As of 2013, lead-based ammunition production is the second-largest annual use of lead in the US, accounting for over 60,000 metric tons consumed in 2012.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Lead bullets that miss their target or remain in a carcass or body that was never retrieved can enter environmental systems and become toxic to wildlife.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] The US military has experimented with replacing lead with copper as a slug in their green bullets which reduces the dangers posed by lead in the environment as a result of artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Since 2010, this has eliminated over 2000 tons of lead in waste streams.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Hunters are also encouraged to use monolithic bullets, which exclude any lead content.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/ammunition] Unexploded ammunition can remain active for a very long time and poses a significant threat to both humans and the environment.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] Collaborating with Charles Renard, Krebs piloted the first fully controlled free-flight made in the French Army airship *La France*, which was designed in 1884.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] The flight covered 8 km (5.0 mi) in 23 minutes.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] The flight landed back at its starting point.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] On its seven flights the *La France* dirigible returned five times to its starting point.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs and Renard shared the 1886 Ponti prize of the French *Académie des sciences* for their contribution to aerostation.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] In Verne's 1886 novel *Robur The Conqueror*, he writes of "the striking experiments of Captain Krebs and Captain Renard".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1888 Krebs and Gustave Zédé designed the first modern French submarine, the *Gymnote*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] The submarine was fitted with the first naval periscope and the first naval electric gyrocompass.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] The latter allowed the *Gymnote* to force a naval block in 1890.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] From 1884 to 1897 Arthur Krebs modernized the *Ville de Paris* fire department; not only its equipment but its organisation as well.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] His work left a lasting impression in this elite corps.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] In May 1896 Arthur Krebs patented a new automobile, fitted with an electromagnetic gearbox and a layout of the front wheels which re-centred them when the steering wheel was left alone.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] Today this is known as the Castor angle.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] The Panhard et Levassor company acquired a license to build 500 cars under the name of Clement-Panhard between 1898 and 1902 featuring this innovation.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs succeeded Levassor as Panhard et Levassor's general manager from 1897 to 1916.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] He transformed the Panhard et Levassor Company into one of the largest and most profitable automobile manufacturers before World War I.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1898 Krebs replaced the tiller with an inclined steering wheel for the Panhard et Levassor car he designed for the Paris-Amsterdam race which ran from 7 to 13 July 1898.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] Fernand Charron won that race on a four-cylinder Panhard et Levassor.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] At the end of 1898, C S Rolls introduced the first car in Britain fitted with wheel steering when he imported a 6 hp Panhard et Levassor from France.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1902 Krebs invented the automatic diaphragm carburettor which gave cars continuous power during acceleration by providing a constant air-fuel ratio at all times; this also led to dramatic improvement in fuel economy.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1906 Krebs traveled to the United States to plead in the Selden Case, associated with Henry Ford.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] Also, Krebs contributed significantly to improve the Systeme Panhard (engine in front, rear wheel drive) which became universally adopted before World War II.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1909 Krebs became interested in the Knight patent (sleeve valve engine).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] He was also the first person in France to build that type of engine which Panhard et Levassor would produce during the thirty years leading up to World War II.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] He made contributions to automotive racing with his powerful cars and motorboats.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1911 Krebs invented the first elastomeric flexible coupling (cf.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] It is known in French as the *Flector* joint.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] This device is still widely used today in industry for power transmission as a *tyre coupling*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] The truck was meant for military and civil purposes.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1911, jointly with the Chatillon Co, Krebs designed the *Tracteur Chatillon-Panhard* all-terrain truck.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] The truck had four wheel drive and four wheel steering and many were used during World War I as artillery tractors.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs also utilized his former military membership to supply the French Army with engines and vehicles including the 1904 Genty Armored car, the 1916 St Chamond tank, the Chatillon-Panhard 4x4 truck, and others.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1960, the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) named Krebs Glacier, a glacier flowing west into the head of Charlotte Bay on the west coast of Graham Land in the Antarctic continent, after Krebs.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1934, several months before Arthur Krebs's death, he was made a Commandeur of the Legion of Honour for his work in Aeronautics and for his contributions to the automotive industry.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] François Frézeau de La Frézelière was born into the noble Frézeau de La Frézelière family.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] From 1651, the family's residence was the chateau at Monts-sur-Guesnes.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] The family produced many soldiers during the wars of the 16th century and 17th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Many of these soldiers were especially proficient in the handling of artillery, including François Frézeau de La Frézelière who was promoted to Lieutenant General.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Frézelière's son Charles-Madeleine Frézeau de la Frézelière (4 September 1654 – 4 November 1702) became the colonel of the *Frézelière* Dragoon Regiment and resigned from the army in 1679.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] He studied at the College of Sorbonne, became a Jesuit, and ultimately became the Bishop of La Rochelle on 27 June 1694.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] By the 1690s, French cannons were produced in the following classes according to the weight of the round shot they fired: 33-pounder, 24-pounder, 16-pounder, 12-pounder, 8-pounder, and 4-pounder.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Each of these were produced in three types.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] *Doubly-fortified* used the thickest metal and fired a gunpowder charge equal in weight to the round shot.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] *Legitimate* used metal of middling thickness and fired a charge four-fifths the weight of the shot.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] *Bastard* used the thinnest metal and fired a charge two-thirds the weight of the shot.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Gun barrels were designed to protrude from a fortified embrasure, so that they were all 10 or 11 ft (3.0 or 3.4 m) long.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] A shorter gun barrel could cause damage to the fortification when the cannon fired.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] The problem was that the long gun barrels made even the smaller caliber cannons very heavy, making them difficult to use as field artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] The Spanish gunner Antonio Gonzales developed a light artillery system in 1679.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Gonzales did this by producing cannons with a spherical powder chamber.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] The spherical chamber allowed the gunpowder charge to burn faster and detonate more violently.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] The new configuration allowed the gunpowder charge to be reduced from two-thirds of the weight of the round shot to one-third of the weight.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Because the charge was reduced, the cannon's weight could be significantly decreased without causing the gun to burst.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Though the charge was reduced, it was found that the round shot retained the same penetrating power as the shot fired with the heavier charge.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] The new 4-pounder was almost the same weight as Lennart Torstensson's Swedish cast iron guns from the Thirty Years' War.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Frézelière liked the idea and incorporated Gonzales' lighter cannons into the *Artillerie de Nouvelle Invention*, though the system was never officially accepted.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] The cannons of the *Nouvelle Invention* were lighter but they suffered from a recoil problem.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] The more powerful explosion of the gunpowder charge caused severe damage to the existing gun carriages.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Another problem was that the larger gun chamber could not be properly swabbed out with a wet rammer.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] This meant that still-burning material might still be inside the chamber.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Any attempt to load more gunpowder could cause a premature detonation, causing severe injury or death to the man loading the gun.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Finally, the shorter gun barrels meant that firing the cannons caused damage to the fortifications.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Frézelière tried to overcome all these problems.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] He experimented with a pear-shaped chamber, but this did not solve the problem.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] He produced cannons with slightly longer gun barrels.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] He built sturdier gun carriages and better gun trails, but they were still not satisfactory.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] He melted down the old culverins in the fortresses on the eastern frontier of France and founded new cannons of the *Nouvelle Invention*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] The conservative artillery officers strenuously opposed these reforms and after Frézelière's death all the *Nouvelle Invention* cannons were recast as longer and heavier artillery pieces.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] In 1720, the *Artillerie de Nouvelle Invention* was suppressed.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] In 1732, the Vallière system was introduced by Jean-Florent de Vallière.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] It standardized the calibers of all French cannons into 24-pounders, 16-pounders, 12-pounders, 8-pounders, and 4-pounders.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillerie-de-nouvelle-invention] Unfortunately, the smaller calibers were too heavy to be efficiently used as field artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Artillery began to be used in France in the 14th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] The first depiction of a cannon in Europe appeared in Walter de Milemete's 1326 *De nobilitatibus, sapientiis, et prudentiis regum*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Small rudimentary weapons such as the pot-de-fer or the portable bâton à feu were introduced.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] At this early stage, cannon would fire either stone balls or metal pellets.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] The 14th century saw considerable development of the new weapons in France and in Western Europe in general, especially with the outbreak of the Hundred Years' War (1337–1453).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Cannons were soon used at sea, with ships being used as a firing platform.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Small guns projecting quarrels or lead pellets were used at the 1340 Battle of Sluys, and in the French defence of Tournai in August 1340.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Edward III used similar weapons at the Battle of Crécy in 1346, and in the Siege of Calais in 1347.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] "Ribaldis" were first mentioned in the English Privy Wardrobe accounts during preparations for the Battle of Crécy between 1345 and 1346.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Cannons evolved considerably towards the end of the century with the collapse of the Treaty of Brétigny and the resumption of the war in 1369.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Until 1370, cannons were essentially small weapons of 10 to 20 kg (20 to 40 lbs), made of brass or copper.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] After that point, larger guns appeared, made of wrought iron or cast iron.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] During the 1375 siege of Saint-Sauveur-le-Vicomte, French troops successfully breached the walls of the fortress with guns weighing over 1 ton, and firing 50 kg stone balls.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] The English trailed behind French developments in the area and only had a few such weapons before 1400.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] By the end of the century, new firearm types appeared, such as a variety of hand guns, small mortars and ribaudequins.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] These complemented, but did not replace, heavier artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] By the early 15th century, both armies had a wide variety of gunpowder weapons.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Large guns were developed, known as bombards (French *bombardes*), weighing up to 3 tonnes and firing stone balls of up to 150 kg (300 lbs), which seem to have been more prevalent among the French than among the English until 1420.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Such bombards were often made by welding bars of wrought iron together and holding them inside circular bracelets, a process known as *"à tonoille"*, similar to that involving the manufacture of wine barrels (*tonneaux*).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] The first Western image of a battle with cannon goes back to the Siege of Orléans in 1429, in which both the English and the French side are depicted with firearms.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] French cannon killed the English commander Thomas Montagu in 1428.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Joan of Arc used cannon effectively during the Loire campaign in 1429.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Portable hand cannons, the ancestors of modern firearms, continued to be used on a wide scale, sometimes even by mounted soldiers.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Small portable arms were also developed such as *serpentines* and *couleuvrines*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] They were not able, however, to replace the widespread longbows or crossbows during the Hundred Years' War.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] In contrast, cannon took on a major role in siege warfare, where they came to replace traditional wooden siege engines of the types used since antiquity.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] From the 1430s, the artillery of Charles VII was managed by Master Gunner Jean Bureau.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Artillery was key to the French successes at Meaux (1439), Pontoise (1441), BCaen and during the Norman Campaign (1449–1450).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] French artillery was used with great efficiency at the 1453 Battle of Castillon, in which grouped and entrenched cannons decimated the English army, killing the commander John Talbot.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-of-france-in-the-middle-ages] Artillery also started to affect military architecture, leading to the development of lower, thicker walls in order to better resist the effect of cannonballs.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Originally, the word "artillery" referred to any group of soldiers primarily armed with some form of manufactured weapon or armour.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Since the introduction of gunpowder and cannon, "artillery" has largely meant cannon, and in contemporary usage, usually refers to shell-firing guns, howitzers, and mortars (collectively called *barrel artillery*, *cannon artillery* or *gun artillery*) and rocket artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In common speech, the word "artillery" is often used to refer to individual devices, along with their accessories and fittings, although these assemblages are more properly called "equipment".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] However, there is no generally recognized generic term for a gun, howitzer, mortar, and so forth: the United States uses "artillery piece", but most English-speaking armies use "gun" and "mortar".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The projectiles fired are typically either "shot" (if solid) or "shell" (if not solid).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Historically, variants of solid shot including canister, chain shot and grapeshot were also used.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] "Shell" is a widely used generic term for a projectile, which is a component of munitions.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] By association, artillery may also refer to the arm of service that customarily operates such engines.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In some armies, the artillery arm has operated field, coastal, anti-aircraft, and anti-tank artillery; in others these have been separate arms, and with some nations coastal has been a naval or marine responsibility.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In the 20th century, target acquisition devices (such as radar) and techniques (such as sound ranging and flash spotting) emerged, primarily for artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These are usually utilized by one or more of the artillery arms.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The widespread adoption of indirect fire in the early 20th century introduced the need for specialist data for field artillery, notably survey and meteorological, and in some armies, provision of these are the responsibility of the artillery arm.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The majority of combat deaths in the Napoleonic Wars, World War I, and World War II were caused by artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In 1944, Joseph Stalin said in a speech that artillery was "the god of war".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Although not called by that name, siege engines performing the role recognizable as artillery have been employed in warfare since antiquity.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The first known catapult was developed in Syracuse in 399 BC.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Until the introduction of gunpowder into western warfare, artillery was dependent upon mechanical energy, which not only severely limited the kinetic energy of the projectiles, but also required the construction of very large engines to accumulate sufficient energy.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] From the Middle Ages through most of the modern era, artillery pieces on land were moved by horse-drawn gun carriages.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In the contemporary era, artillery pieces and their crew relied on wheeled or tracked vehicles as transportation.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These land versions of artillery were dwarfed by railway guns; the largest of these large-calibre guns ever conceived – Project Babylon of the Supergun affair – was theoretically capable of putting a satellite into orbit.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Artillery used by naval forces has also changed significantly, with missiles generally replacing guns in surface warfare.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Over the course of military history, projectiles were manufactured from a wide variety of materials, into a wide variety of shapes, using many different methods in which to target structural/defensive works and inflict enemy casualties.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The engineering applications for ordnance delivery have likewise changed significantly over time, encompassing some of the most complex and advanced technologies in use today.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In some armies, the weapon of artillery is the projectile, not the equipment that fires it.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The process of delivering fire onto the target is called gunnery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The actions involved in operating an artillery piece are collectively called "serving the gun" by the "detachment" or gun crew, constituting either direct or indirect artillery fire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The manner in which gunnery crews (or formations) are employed is called artillery support.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] At different periods in history, this may refer to weapons designed to be fired from ground-, sea-, and even air-based weapons platforms.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Some armed forces use the term "gunners" for the soldiers and sailors with the primary function of using artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The gunners and their guns are usually grouped in teams called either "crews" or "detachments".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Several such crews and teams with other functions are combined into a unit of artillery, usually called a battery, although sometimes called a company.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In gun detachments, each role is numbered, starting with "1" the Detachment Commander, and the highest number being the Coverer, the second-in-command.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] "Gunner" is also the lowest rank, and junior non-commissioned officers are "Bombardiers" in some artillery arms.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Batteries are roughly equivalent to a company in the infantry, and are combined into larger military organizations for administrative and operational purposes, either battalions or regiments, depending on the army.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These may be grouped into brigades; the Russian army also groups some brigades into artillery divisions, and the People's Liberation Army has artillery corps.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The term "artillery" also designates a combat arm of most military services when used organizationally to describe units and formations of the national armed forces that operate the weapons.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] During military operations, field artillery has the role of providing support to other arms in combat or of attacking targets, particularly in-depth.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Broadly, these effects fall into two categories, aiming either to suppress or neutralize the enemy, or to cause casualties, damage, and destruction.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] This is mostly achieved by delivering high-explosive munitions to suppress, or inflict casualties on the enemy from casing fragments and other debris and from blast, or by destroying enemy positions, equipment, and vehicles.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Non-lethal munitions, notably smoke, can also suppress or neutralize the enemy by obscuring their view.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Fire may be directed by an artillery observer or another observer, including crewed and uncrewed aircraft, or called onto map coordinates.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Military doctrine has had a significant influence on the core engineering design considerations of artillery ordnance through its history, in seeking to achieve a balance between the delivered volume of fire with ordnance mobility.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] However, during the modern period, the consideration of protecting the gunners also arose due to the late-19th-century introduction of the new generation of infantry weapons using conoidal bullet, better known as the Minié ball, with a range almost as long as that of field artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The gunners' increasing proximity to and participation in direct combat against other combat arms and attacks by aircraft made the introduction of a gun shield necessary.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The problems of how to employ a fixed or horse-towed gun in mobile warfare necessitated the development of new methods of transporting the artillery into combat.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Two distinct forms of artillery were developed: the towed gun, used primarily to attack or defend a fixed-line; and the self-propelled gun, intended to accompany a mobile force and to provide continuous fire support and/or suppression.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These influences have guided the development of artillery ordnance, systems, organizations, and operations until the present, with artillery systems capable of providing support at ranges from as little as 100 m to the intercontinental ranges of ballistic missiles.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The only combat in which artillery is unable to take part is close-quarters combat, with the possible exception of artillery reconnaissance teams.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The word as used in the current context originated in the Middle Ages.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] One suggestion is that it comes from French *atelier*, meaning the place where manual work is done.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Hence, the naming of the Honourable Artillery Company, which was essentially an infantry unit until the 19th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Another suggestion is that it comes from the Italian *arte de tirare* (art of shooting), coined by one of the first theorists on the use of artillery, Niccolò Tartaglia.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The term was used by Girolamo Ruscelli (died 1566) in his *Precepts of Modern Militia* published posthumously in 1572.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Mechanical systems used for throwing ammunition in ancient warfare, also known as "engines of war", like the catapult, onager, trebuchet, and ballista, are also referred to by military historians as artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] During medieval times, more types of artillery were developed, most notably the counterweight trebuchet.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Traction trebuchets, using manpower to launch projectiles, have been used in ancient China since the 4th century as anti-personnel weapons.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The much more powerful counterweight trebuchet was invented in the eastern Mediterranean region in the 12th century, with the earliest definite attestation in 1187.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Early Chinese artillery had vase-like shapes.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] This includes the "long range awe inspiring" cannon dated from 1350 and found in the 14th century Ming dynasty treatise *Huolongjing*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] With the development of better metallurgy techniques, later cannons abandoned the vase shape of early Chinese artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] This change can be seen in the bronze "thousand ball thunder cannon", an early example of field artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These small, crude weapons diffused into the Middle East (the *madfaa*) and reached Europe in the 13th century, in a very limited manner.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In Asia, Mongols adopted the Chinese artillery and used it effectively in the great conquest.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] By the late 14th century, Chinese rebels used organized artillery and cavalry to push Mongols out.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] As small smooth-bore barrels, these were initially cast in iron or bronze around a core, with the first drilled bore ordnance recorded in operation near Seville in 1247.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] They fired lead, iron, or stone balls, sometimes large arrows and on occasions simply handfuls of whatever scrap came to hand.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] During the Hundred Years' War, these weapons became more common, initially as the bombard and later the cannon.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] While there were many early attempts at breech-loading designs, a lack of engineering knowledge rendered these even more dangerous to use than muzzle-loaders.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In 1415, the Portuguese invaded the Mediterranean port town of Ceuta.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] While it is difficult to confirm the use of firearms in the siege of the city, it is known the Portuguese defended it thereafter with firearms, namely *bombardas*, *colebratas*, and *falconetes*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In 1419, Sultan Abu Sa'id led an army to reconquer the fallen city, and Marinids brought cannons and used them in the assault on Ceuta.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Finally, hand-held firearms and riflemen appear in Morocco, in 1437, in an expedition against the people of Tangiers.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] It is clear these weapons had developed into several different forms, from small guns to large artillery pieces.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The artillery revolution in Europe caught on during the Hundred Years' War and changed the way that battles were fought.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In the preceding decades, the English had even used a gunpowder-like weapon in military campaigns against the Scottish.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] However, at this time, the cannons used in battle were very small and not particularly powerful.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Cannons were only useful for the defense of a castle, as demonstrated at Breteuil in 1356, when the besieged English used a cannon to destroy an attacking French assault tower.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] By the end of the 14th century, cannons were only powerful enough to knock in roofs, and could not penetrate castle walls.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] However, a major change occurred between 1420 and 1430, when artillery became much more powerful and could now batter strongholds and fortresses quite efficiently.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The English, French, and Burgundians all advanced in military technology, and as a result the traditional advantage that went to the defense in a siege was lost.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Cannons during this period were elongated, and the recipe for gunpowder was improved to make it three times as powerful as before.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These changes led to the increased power in the artillery weapons of the time.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Joan of Arc encountered gunpowder weaponry several times.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] When she led the French against the English at the Battle of Tourelles, in 1430, she faced heavy gunpowder fortifications, and yet her troops prevailed in that battle.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In addition, she led assaults against the English-held towns of Jargeau, Meung, and Beaugency, all with the support of large artillery units.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] When she led the assault on Paris, Joan faced stiff artillery fire, especially from the suburb of St.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Denis, which ultimately led to her defeat in this battle.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In April 1430, she went to battle against the Burgundians, whose support was purchased by the English.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] At this time, the Burgundians had the strongest and largest gunpowder arsenal among the European powers, and yet the French, under Joan of Arc's leadership, were able to beat back the Burgundians and defend themselves.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] As a result, most of the battles of the Hundred Years' War that Joan of Arc participated in were fought with gunpowder artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The army of Mehmet the Conqueror, which conquered Constantinople in 1453, included both artillery and foot soldiers armed with gunpowder weapons.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The Ottomans brought to the siege sixty-nine guns in fifteen separate batteries and trained them at the walls of the city.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The barrage of Ottoman cannon fire lasted forty days, and they are estimated to have fired 19,320 times.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Artillery also played a decisive role in the Battle of St.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Early cannon were not always reliable; King James II of Scotland was killed by the accidental explosion of one of his own cannon, imported from Flanders, at the siege of Roxburgh Castle in 1460.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The able use of artillery supported to a large measure the expansion and defense of the Portuguese Empire, as it was a necessary tool that allowed the Portuguese to face overwhelming odds both on land and sea from Morocco to Asia.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] During the reign of King Manuel (1495–1521) more than 2000 cannons were sent to Morocco for garrison defense, with over 3000 cannons estimated to have been required during that 26-year period.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] An especially noticeable division between siege guns and anti-personnel guns enhanced the use and effectiveness of Portuguese firearms above contemporary powers, making cannon the most essential element in the Portuguese arsenal.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The most popular in Portuguese arsenals was the *berço*, a 5 cm, one pounder bronze breech-loading cannon that weighted 150 kg with an effective range of 600 meters.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] A tactical innovation the Portuguese introduced in fort defense was the use of combinations of projectiles against massed assaults.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] An innovation which Portugal adopted in advance of other European powers was fuse-delayed action shells, and were commonly used in 1505.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Although dangerous, their effectiveness meant a sixth of all rounds used by the Portuguese in Morocco were of the fused-shell variety.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The new Ming Dynasty established the "Divine Engine Battalion" (神机营), which specialized in various types of artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Light cannons and cannons with multiple volleys were developed.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In a campaign to suppress a local minority rebellion near today's Burmese border, "the Ming army used a 3-line method of arquebuses/muskets to destroy an elephant formation".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] When the Portuguese and Spanish arrived at Southeast Asia, they found that the local kingdoms were already using cannons.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Portuguese and Spanish invaders were unpleasantly surprised and even outgunned on occasion.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] 1514 said that the inhabitants of Java were great masters in casting artillery and very good artillerymen.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] They made many one-pounder cannons (cetbang or rentaka), long muskets, *spingarde* (arquebus), *schioppi* (hand cannon), Greek fire, guns (cannons), and other fire-works.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In all aspects the Javanese were considered excellent in casting artillery, and in the knowledge of using it.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In 1513, the Javanese fleet led by Pati Unus sailed to attack Portuguese Malacca "with much artillery made in Java, for the Javanese are skilled in founding and casting, and in all works in iron, over and above what they have in India".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] By the early 16th century, the Javanese had already started locally-producing large guns, which were dubbed "sacred cannon[s]" or "holy cannon[s]" and have survived up to the present day – though in limited numbers.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These cannons varied between 180 and 260-pounders, weighing anywhere between 3–8 tons, measuring between 3–6 m.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Between 1593 and 1597, about 200,000 Korean and Chinese troops which fought against Japan in Korea actively used heavy artillery in both siege and field combat.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Korean forces mounted artillery in ships as naval guns, providing an advantage against Japanese navy which used *Kunikuzushi* (国崩し – Japanese breech-loading swivel gun) and *Ōzutsu* (大筒 – large size Tanegashima) as their largest firearms.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In the 16th century Ottoman Empire, Humbaracıs were founded.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Bombards were of value mainly in sieges.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] A famous Ottoman example, the "Basilic", used at the siege of Constantinople in 1453, that weighed around 19 tonnes.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] It could fire a stone ball of 1,500 pounds (680 kg) more than 1 mile (1.6 km), but could only fire seven or eight times a day.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The gun took two hundred men and sixty oxen to move, with a further 250 labourers to improve the road in front of it, travelling at little more than 3 kilometres (1.9 mi) per day.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] It formed part of a battery of 70 bronze guns, of which 19 were very large; together they fired 4,000 balls over 53 days and breached the walls in several places, although the final assault was enabled by a traitor opening a postern gate.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These guns were sometimes cast at the site of the siege itself.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Bombards developed in Europe were massive smoothbore weapons distinguished by their lack of a field carriage, immobility once emplaced, highly individual design, and noted unreliability (in 1460 James II, King of Scots, was killed when one exploded at the siege of Roxburgh).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Their large size precluded the barrels being cast and they were constructed out of metal staves or rods bound together with hoops like a barrel, giving their name to the gun barrel.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The use of the word "cannon" marks the introduction in the 15th century of a dedicated field carriage with axle, trail and animal-drawn limber—this produced mobile field pieces that could move and support an army in action, rather than being found only in the siege and static defenses.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The first land-based mobile weapon is usually credited to Jan Žižka, who deployed his oxen-hauled cannon during the Hussite Wars of Bohemia (1418–1424).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] However, cannons were still large and cumbersome.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] With the rise of musketry in the 16th century, cannon were largely (though not entirely) displaced from the battlefield—the cannon were too slow and cumbersome to be used and too easily lost to a rapid enemy advance.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The combining of shot and powder into a single unit, a cartridge, occurred in the 1620s with a simple fabric bag, and was quickly adopted by all nations.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] It speeded loading and made it safer, but unexpelled bag fragments were an additional fouling in the gun barrel and a new tool—a worm—was introduced to remove them.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Gustavus Adolphus is identified as the general who made cannon an effective force on the battlefield—pushing the development of much lighter and smaller weapons and deploying them in far greater numbers than previously.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The outcome of battles was still determined by the clash of infantry.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Shells, explosive-filled fused projectiles, were in use by the 15th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The development of specialized pieces—shipboard artillery, howitzers and mortars—was also begun in this period.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] More esoteric designs, like the multi-barrel *ribauldequin* (known as "organ guns"), were also produced.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The 1650 book by Kazimierz Siemienowicz *Artis Magnae Artilleriae pars prima* was one of the most important contemporary publications on the subject of artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] For over two centuries this work was used in Europe as a basic artillery manual.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Modern rocket artillery can trace its heritage back to the Mysorean rockets of Mysore.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Their first recorded use was in 1780 during the battles of the Second, Third and Fourth Mysore Wars.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The wars fought between the British East India Company and the Kingdom of Mysore in India made use of the rockets as a weapon.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In the Battle of Pollilur, the Siege of Seringapatam (1792) and in Battle of Seringapatam in 1799, these rockets were used with considerable effect against the British.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] After the wars, several Mysore rockets were sent to England, but experiments with heavier payloads were unsuccessful.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] With the Napoleonic Wars, artillery experienced changes in both physical design and operation.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Rather than being overseen by "mechanics", artillery was viewed as its own service branch with the capability of dominating the battlefield.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The success of the French artillery companies was at least in part due to the presence of specially trained artillery officers leading and coordinating during the chaos of battle.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Napoleon, himself a former artillery officer, perfected the tactic of massed artillery batteries unleashed upon a critical point in his enemies' line as a prelude to a decisive infantry and cavalry assault.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Physically, cannons continued to become smaller and lighter.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] During the Seven Years War, King Frederick II of Prussia used these advances to deploy horse artillery that could move throughout the battlefield.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Frederick also introduced the reversible iron ramrod, which was much more resistant to breakage than older wooden designs.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The reversibility aspect also helped increase the rate of fire, since a soldier would no longer have to worry about what end of the ramrod they were using.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Jean-Baptiste de Gribeauval, a French artillery engineer, introduced the standardization of cannon design in the mid-18th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] He developed a 6-inch (150 mm) field howitzer whose gun barrel, carriage assembly and ammunition specifications were made uniform for all French cannons.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The standardized interchangeable parts of these cannons down to the nuts, bolts and screws made their mass production and repair much easier.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] While the Gribeauval system made for more efficient production and assembly, the carriages used were heavy and the gunners were forced to march on foot (instead of riding on the limber and gun as in the British system).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Each cannon was named for the weight of its projectiles, giving us variants such as 4, 8, and 12, indicating the weight in pounds.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The projectiles themselves included solid balls or canister containing lead bullets or other material.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These canister shots acted as massive shotguns, peppering the target with hundreds of projectiles at close range.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The solid balls, known as round shot, was most effective when fired at shoulder-height across a flat, open area.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The ball would tear through the ranks of the enemy or bounce along the ground breaking legs and ankles.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The development of modern artillery occurred in the mid to late 19th century as a result of the convergence of various improvements in the underlying technology.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Advances in metallurgy allowed for the construction of breech-loading rifled guns that could fire at a much greater muzzle velocity.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] After the British artillery was shown up in the Crimean War as having barely changed since the Napoleonic Wars, the industrialist William Armstrong was awarded a contract by the government to design a new piece of artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Production started in 1855 at the Elswick Ordnance Company and the Royal Arsenal at Woolwich, and the outcome was the revolutionary Armstrong Gun, which marked the birth of modern artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Three of its features particularly stand out.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] First, the piece was rifled, which allowed for a much more accurate and powerful action.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Although rifling had been tried on small arms since the 15th century, the necessary machinery to accurately rifle artillery was not available until the mid-19th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Martin von Wahrendorff, and Joseph Whitworth independently produced rifled cannon in the 1840s, but it was Armstrong's gun that was first to see widespread use during the Crimean War.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The cast iron shell of the Armstrong gun was similar in shape to a Minié ball and had a thin lead coating which made it fractionally larger than the gun's bore and which engaged with the gun's rifling grooves to impart spin to the shell.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] This spin, together with the elimination of windage as a result of the tight fit, enabled the gun to achieve greater range and accuracy than existing smooth-bore muzzle-loaders with a smaller powder charge.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Although attempts at breech-loading mechanisms had been made since medieval times, the essential engineering problem was that the mechanism could not withstand the explosive charge.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] It was only with the advances in metallurgy and precision engineering capabilities during the Industrial Revolution that Armstrong was able to construct a viable solution.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The gun combined all the properties that make up an effective artillery piece.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The gun was mounted on a carriage in such a way as to return the gun to firing position after the recoil.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] What made the gun really revolutionary lay in the technique of the construction of the gun barrel that allowed it to withstand much more powerful explosive forces.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The "built-up" method involved assembling the barrel with wrought-iron (later mild steel was used) tubes of successively smaller diameter.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The tube would then be heated to allow it to expand and fit over the previous tube.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] When it cooled the gun would contract although not back to its original size, which allowed an even pressure along the walls of the gun which was directed inward against the outward forces that the gun's firing exerted on the barrel.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Armstrong's system was adopted in 1858, initially for "special service in the field" and initially he produced only smaller artillery pieces, 6-pounder (2.5 in/64 mm) mountain or light field guns, 9-pounder (3 in/76 mm) guns for horse artillery, and 12-pounder (3 inches /76 mm) field guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The first cannon to contain all 'modern' features is generally considered to be the French 75 of 1897.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The gun used cased ammunition, was breech-loading, had modern sights, and a self-contained firing mechanism.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] It was the first field gun to include a hydro-pneumatic recoil mechanism, which kept the gun's trail and wheels perfectly still during the firing sequence.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Since it did not need to be re-aimed after each shot, the crew could fire as soon as the barrel returned to its resting position.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In typical use, the French 75 could deliver fifteen rounds per minute on its target, either shrapnel or melinite high-explosive, up to about 5 miles (8,500 m) away.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Its firing rate could even reach close to 30 rounds per minute, albeit only for a very short time and with a highly experienced crew.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These were rates that contemporary bolt action rifles could not match.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Indirect fire, the firing of a projectile without relying on direct line of sight between the gun and the target, possibly dates back to the 16th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Early battlefield use of indirect fire may have occurred at Paltzig in July 1759, when the Russian artillery fired over the tops of trees, and at the Battle of Waterloo, where a battery of the Royal Horse Artillery fired shrapnel indirectly against advancing French troops.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In 1882, Russian Lieutenant Colonel KG Guk published *Indirect Fire for Field Artillery*, which provided a practical method of using aiming points for indirect fire by describing, "all the essentials of aiming points, crest clearance, and corrections to fire by an observer".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] A few years later, the Richtfläche (lining-plane) sight was invented in Germany and provided a means of indirect laying in azimuth, complementing the clinometers for indirect laying in elevation which already existed.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Despite conservative opposition within the German army, indirect fire was adopted as doctrine by the 1890s.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In the early 1900s, Goertz in Germany developed an optical sight for azimuth laying.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] It quickly replaced the lining-plane; in English, it became the 'Dial Sight' (UK) or 'Panoramic Telescope' (US).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In the next 15 years leading up to World War I, the techniques of indirect fire became available for all types of artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Indirect fire was the defining characteristic of 20th-century artillery and led to undreamt of changes in the amount of artillery, its tactics, organisation, and techniques, most of which occurred during World War I.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] An implication of indirect fire and improving guns was increasing range between gun and target, this increased the time of flight and the vertex of the trajectory.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The result was decreasing accuracy (the increasing distance between the target and the mean point of impact of the shells aimed at it) caused by the increasing effects of non-standard conditions.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Indirect firing data was based on standard conditions including a specific muzzle velocity, zero wind, air temperature and density, and propellant temperature.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In practice, this standard combination of conditions almost never existed, they varied throughout the day and day to day, and the greater the time of flight, the greater the inaccuracy.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] An added complication was the need for survey to accurately fix the coordinates of the gun position and provide accurate orientation for the guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Of course, targets had to be accurately located, but by 1916, air photo interpretation techniques enabled this, and ground survey techniques could sometimes be used.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] In 1914, the methods of correcting firing data for the actual conditions were often convoluted, and the availability of data about actual conditions was rudimentary or non-existent, the assumption was that fire would always be ranged (adjusted).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] British heavy artillery worked energetically to progressively solve all these problems from late 1914 onwards, and by early 1918, had effective processes in place for both field and heavy artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These processes enabled 'map-shooting', later called 'predicted fire'; it meant that effective fire could be delivered against an accurately located target without ranging.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Nevertheless, the mean point of impact was still some tens of yards from the target-centre aiming point.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] It was not precision fire, but it was good enough for concentrations and barrages.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These processes remain in use into the 21st century with refinements to calculations enabled by computers and improved data capture about non-standard conditions.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The British Major General Henry Hugh Tudor pioneered armour and artillery cooperation at the breakthrough Battle of Cambrai.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The improvements in providing and using data for non-standard conditions (propellant temperature, muzzle velocity, wind, air temperature, and barometric pressure) were developed by the major combatants throughout the war and enabled effective predicted fire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The effectiveness of this was demonstrated by the British in 1917 (at Cambrai) and by Germany the following year (Operation Michael).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] An estimated 75,000 French soldiers were casualties of friendly artillery fire in the four years of World War I.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Modern artillery is most obviously distinguished by its long range, firing an explosive shell or rocket and a mobile carriage for firing and transport.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] However, its most important characteristic is the use of indirect fire, whereby the firing equipment is aimed without seeing the target through its sights.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Indirect fire emerged at the beginning of the 20th century and was greatly enhanced by the development of predicted fire methods in World War I.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] However, indirect fire was area fire; it was and is not suitable for destroying point targets; its primary purpose is area suppression.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Nevertheless, by the late 1970s precision-guided munitions started to appear, notably the US 155 mm Copperhead and its Soviet 152 mm Krasnopol equivalent that had success in Indian service.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] These relied on laser designation to 'illuminate' the target that the shell homed onto.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] However, in the early 21st century, the Global Positioning System (GPS) enabled relatively cheap and accurate guidance for shells and missiles, notably the US 155 mm Excalibur and the 227 mm GMLRS rocket.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The introduction of these led to a new issue, the need for very accurate three dimensional target coordinates—the mensuration process.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Weapons covered by the term 'modern artillery' include "cannon" artillery (such as howitzer, mortar, and field gun) and rocket artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Certain smaller-caliber mortars are more properly designated small arms rather than artillery, albeit indirect-fire small arms.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] This term also came to include coastal artillery which traditionally defended coastal areas against seaborne attack and controlled the passage of ships.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] With the advent of powered flight at the start of the 20th century, artillery also included ground-based anti-aircraft batteries.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] The term "artillery" has traditionally not been used for projectiles with internal guidance systems, preferring the term "missilery", though some modern artillery units employ surface-to-surface missiles.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p01] Advances in terminal guidance systems for small munitions has allowed large-caliber guided projectiles to be developed, blurring this distinction.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Fuzes are the devices that initiate an artillery projectile, either to detonate its High Explosive (HE) filling or eject its cargo (illuminating flare or smoke canisters being examples).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The official military spelling is "fuze".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] However, base fuzes have been used with armor-piercing shells and for squash head (High-Explosive Squash Head (HESH) or High Explosive, Plastic (HEP) anti-tank shells).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] At least one nuclear shell and its non-nuclear spotting version also used a multi-deck mechanical time fuze fitted into its base.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Impact fuzes were, and in some armies remain, the standard fuze for HE projectiles.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Their default action is normally 'superquick', some have had a 'graze' action which allows them to penetrate light cover and others have 'delay'.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Delay fuzes allow the shell to penetrate the ground before exploding.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Armor or Concrete-Piercing (AP or CP) fuzes are specially hardened.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] During World War I and later, ricochet fire with delay or graze fuzed HE shells, fired with a flat angle of descent, was used to achieve airburst.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] HE shells can be fitted with other fuzes.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Airburst fuzes usually have a combined airburst and impact function.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] However, until the introduction of proximity fuzes, the airburst function was mostly used with cargo munitions—for example, shrapnel, illumination, and smoke.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The larger calibers of anti-aircraft artillery are almost always used airburst.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Airburst fuzes have to have the fuze length (running time) set on them.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] This is done just before firing using either a wrench or a fuze setter pre-set to the required fuze length.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Early airburst fuzes used igniferous timers which lasted into the second half of the 20th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Mechanical time fuzes appeared in the early part of the century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] These required a means of powering them.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The Thiel mechanism used a spring and escapement (i.e.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] 'clockwork'), Junghans used centrifugal force and gears, and Dixi used centrifugal force and balls.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] From about 1980, electronic time fuzes started replacing mechanical ones for use with cargo munitions.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Proximity fuzes have been of two types: photo-electric or radar.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The former was not very successful and seems only to have been used with British anti-aircraft artillery 'unrotated projectiles' (rockets) in World War II.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Radar proximity fuzes were a big improvement over the mechanical (time) fuzes which they replaced.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Mechanical time fuzes required an accurate calculation of their running time, which was affected by non-standard conditions.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] With HE (requiring a burst 20 to 30 feet (9.1 m) above the ground), if this was very slightly wrong the rounds would either hit the ground or burst too high.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Accurate running time was less important with cargo munitions that burst much higher.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The first radar proximity fuzes (perhaps originally codenamed 'VT' and later called Variable Time (VT)) were invented by the British and developed by the US and initially used against aircraft in World War II.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Their ground use was delayed for fear of the enemy recovering 'blinds' (artillery shells which failed to detonate) and copying the fuze.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The first proximity fuzes were designed to detonate about 30 feet (9.1 m) above the ground.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] These air-bursts are much more lethal against personnel than ground bursts because they deliver a greater proportion of useful fragments and deliver them into terrain where a prone soldier would be protected from ground bursts.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] However, proximity fuzes can suffer premature detonation because of the moisture in heavy rain clouds.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] This led to 'Controlled Variable Time' (CVT) after World War II.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] These fuzes have a mechanical timer that switched on the radar about 5 seconds before expected impact, they also detonated on impact.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The proximity fuze emerged on the battlefields of Europe in late December 1944.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Artillery's "Christmas present", and were much appreciated when they arrived during the Battle of the Bulge.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] They were also used to great effect in anti-aircraft projectiles in the Pacific against *kamikaze* as well as in Britain against V-1 flying bombs.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Electronic multi-function fuzes started to appear around 1980.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Using solid-state electronics they were relatively cheap and reliable, and became the standard fitted fuze in operational ammunition stocks in some western armies.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The early versions were often limited to proximity airburst, albeit with height of burst options, and impact.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Some offered a go/no-go functional test through the fuze setter.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Later versions introduced induction fuze setting and testing instead of physically placing a fuze setter on the fuze.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The latest, such as Junghan's DM84U provide options giving, superquick, delay, a choice of proximity heights of burst, time and a choice of foliage penetration depths.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The projectile is the munition or "bullet" fired downrange.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Projectiles have traditionally been classified as "shot" or "shell", the former being solid and the latter having some form of "payload".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Shells can be divided into three configurations: bursting, base ejection or nose ejection.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The latter is sometimes called the shrapnel configuration.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The most modern is base ejection, which was introduced in World War I.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Base and nose ejection are almost always used with airburst fuzes.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Bursting shells use various types of fuze depending on the nature of the payload and the tactical need at the time.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Most forms of artillery require a propellant to propel the projectile to the target.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Propellant is always a low explosive, which means it deflagrates, rather than detonating like high explosives.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The shell is accelerated to a high velocity in a very short time by the rapid generation of gas from the burning propellant.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] This high pressure is achieved by burning the propellant in a contained area, either the chamber of a gun barrel or the combustion chamber of a rocket motor.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Until the late 19th century, the only available propellant was black powder.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] It had many disadvantages as a propellant; it has relatively low power, requiring large amounts of powder to fire projectiles, and created thick clouds of white smoke that would obscure the targets, betray the positions of guns, and make aiming impossible.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] In 1846, nitrocellulose (also known as guncotton) was discovered, and the high explosive nitroglycerin was discovered at nearly the same time.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Nitrocellulose was significantly more powerful than black powder, and was smokeless.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Early guncotton was unstable, however, and burned very fast and hot, leading to greatly increased barrel wear.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Widespread introduction of smokeless powder would wait until the advent of the double-base powders, which combine nitrocellulose and nitroglycerin to produce powerful, smokeless, stable propellant.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Many other formulations were developed in the following decades, generally trying to find the optimum characteristics of a good artillery propellant – low temperature, high energy, non-corrosive, highly stable, cheap, and easy to manufacture in large quantities.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Propelling charges for barrel artillery can be provided either as cartridge bags or in metal cartridge cases.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Generally, anti-aircraft artillery and smaller-caliber (up to 3" or 76.2 mm) guns use metal cartridge cases that include the round and propellant, similar to a modern rifle cartridge.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] This simplifies loading and is necessary for very high rates of fire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Bagged propellant allows the amount of powder to be raised or lowered, depending on the range to the target.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] It also makes handling of larger shells easier.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Cases and bags require totally different types of breech.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] A metal case holds an integral primer to initiate the propellant and provides the gas seal to prevent the gases leaking out of the breech; this is called obturation.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] With bagged charges, the breech itself provides obturation and holds the primer.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] In either case, the primer is usually percussion, but electrical is also used, and laser ignition is emerging.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Modern 155 mm guns have a primer magazine fitted to their breech.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Because modern field artillery mostly uses indirect fire, the guns have to be part of a system that enables them to attack targets invisible to them, in accordance with the combined arms plan.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] All these calculations to produce a quadrant elevation (or range) and azimuth were done manually using instruments, tabulated, data of the moment, and approximations until battlefield computers started appearing in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] While some early calculators copied the manual method (typically substituting polynomials for tabulated data), computers use a different approach.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] They simulate a shell's trajectory by 'flying' it in short steps and applying data about the conditions affecting the trajectory at each step.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] This simulation is repeated until it produces a quadrant elevation and azimuth that lands the shell within the required 'closing' distance of the target coordinates.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] NATO has a standard ballistic model for computer calculations and has expanded the scope of this into the NATO Armaments Ballistic Kernel (NABK) within the SG2 Shareable (Fire Control) Software Suite (S4).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Supply of artillery ammunition has always been a major component of military logistics.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Up until World War I some armies made artillery responsible for all forward ammunition supply because the load of small arms ammunition was trivial compared to artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Different armies use different approaches to ammunition supply, which can vary with the nature of operations.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Differences include where the logistic service transfers artillery ammunition to artillery, the amount of ammunition carried in units and extent to which stocks are held at unit or battery level.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] A key difference is whether supply is 'push' or 'pull'.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] In the former the 'pipeline' keeps pushing ammunition into formations or units at a defined rate.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] In the latter units fire as tactically necessary and replenish to maintain or reach their authorised holding (which can vary), so the logistic system has to be able to cope with surge and slack.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Artillery types can be categorised in several ways, for example by type or size of weapon or ordnance, by role or by organizational arrangements.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The types of cannon artillery are generally distinguished by the velocity at which they fire projectiles.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Modern field artillery can also be split into two other subcategories: towed and self-propelled.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] As the name suggests, towed artillery has a prime mover, usually an artillery tractor or truck, to move the piece, crew, and ammunition around.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Towed artillery is in some cases equipped with an APU for small displacements.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Self-propelled artillery is permanently mounted on a carriage or vehicle with room for the crew and ammunition and is thus capable of moving quickly from one firing position to another, both to support the fluid nature of modern combat and to avoid counter-battery fire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] It includes mortar carrier vehicles, many of which allow the mortar to be removed from the vehicle and be used dismounted, potentially in terrain in which the vehicle cannot navigate, or in order to avoid detection.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] At the beginning of the modern artillery period, the late 19th century, many armies had three main types of artillery, in some case they were sub-branches within the artillery branch in others they were separate branches or corps.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] After World War I many nations merged these different artillery branches, in some cases keeping some as sub-branches.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Naval artillery disappeared apart from that belonging to marines.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] However, the general switch by artillery to indirect fire before and during World War I led to a reaction in some armies.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The result was accompanying or infantry guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] These were usually small, short range guns, that could be easily man-handled and used mostly for direct fire but some could use indirect fire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Some were operated by the artillery branch but under command of the supported unit.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] In World War II they were joined by self-propelled assault guns, although other armies adopted infantry or close support tanks in armoured branch units for the same purpose, subsequently tanks generally took on the accompanying role.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The three main types of artillery "gun" are field guns, howitzers, and mortars.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] During the 20th century, guns and howitzers have steadily merged in artillery use, making a distinction between the terms somewhat meaningless.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] By the end of the 20th century, true guns with calibers larger than about 60 mm have become very rare in artillery use, the main users being tanks, ships, and a few residual anti-aircraft and coastal guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The term "cannon" is a United States generic term that includes guns, howitzers, and mortars; it is not used in other English speaking armies.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The traditional definitions differentiated between guns and howitzers in terms of maximum elevation (well less than 45° as opposed to close to or greater than 45°), number of charges (one or more than one charge), and having higher or lower muzzle velocity, sometimes indicated by barrel length.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] These three criteria give eight possible combinations, of which guns and howitzers are but two.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] However, modern "howitzers" have higher velocities and longer barrels than the equivalent "guns" of the first half of the 20th century.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] True guns are characterized by long range, having a maximum elevation significantly less than 45°, a high muzzle velocity and hence a relatively long barrel, smooth bore (no rifling) and a single charge.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The latter often led to fixed ammunition where the projectile is locked to the cartridge case.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] There is no generally accepted minimum muzzle velocity or barrel length associated with a gun.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Howitzers can fire at maximum elevations at least close to 45°; elevations up to about 70° are normal for modern howitzers.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Howitzers also have a choice of charges, meaning that the same elevation angle of fire will achieve a different range depending on the charge used.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] They have rifled bores, lower muzzle velocities and shorter barrels than equivalent guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] All this means they can deliver fire with a steep angle of descent.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Because of their multi-charge capability, their ammunition is mostly separate loading (the projectile and propellant are loaded separately).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] That leaves six combinations of the three criteria, some of which have been termed gun howitzers.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] A term first used in the 1930s when howitzers with a relatively high maximum muzzle velocities were introduced, it never became widely accepted, most armies electing to widen the definition of "gun" or "howitzer".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] By the 1960s, most equipment had maximum elevations up to about 70°, were multi-charge, had quite high maximum muzzle velocities and relatively long barrels.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The modern mortar originated in World War I and there were several patterns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] After that war, most mortars settled on the Stokes pattern, characterized by a short barrel, smooth bore, low muzzle velocity, elevation angle of firing generally greater than 45°, and a very simple and light mounting using a "baseplate" on the ground.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The projectile with its integral propelling charge was dropped down the barrel from the muzzle to hit a fixed firing pin.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Since that time, a few mortars have become rifled and adopted breech loading.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] There are other recognized typifying characteristics for artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] One such characteristic is the type of obturation used to seal the chamber and prevent gases escaping through the breech.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] This may use a metal cartridge case that also holds the propelling charge, a configuration called "QF" or "quickfiring" by some nations.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The alternative does not use a metal cartridge case, the propellant being merely bagged or in combustible cases with the breech itself providing all the sealing.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] This is called "BL" or "breech loading" by some nations.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] A second characteristic is the form of propulsion.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Modern equipment can either be towed or self-propelled (SP).
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] A towed gun fires from the ground and any inherent protection is limited to a gun shield.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Towing by horse teams lasted throughout World War II in some armies, but others were fully mechanized with wheeled or tracked gun towing vehicles by the outbreak of that war.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] The size of a towing vehicle depends on the weight of the equipment and the amount of ammunition it has to carry.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] A variation of towed is portee, where the vehicle carries the gun which is dismounted for firing.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] A mortar is sometimes carried in an armored vehicle and can either fire from it or be dismounted to fire from the ground.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Since the early 1960s it has been possible to carry lighter towed guns and most mortars by helicopter.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Even before that, they were parachuted or landed by glider from the time of the first airborne trials in the USSR in the 1930s.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] In SP equipment, the gun is an integral part of the vehicle that carries it.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] SPs first appeared during World War I, but did not really develop until World War II.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] They are mostly tracked vehicles, but wheeled SPs started to appear in the 1970s.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Some SPs have no armor and carry few or no other weapons and ammunition.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Armored SPs usually carry a useful ammunition load.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Early armored SPs were mostly a "casemate" configuration, in essence an open top armored box offering only limited traverse.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] However, most modern armored SPs have a full enclosed armored turret, usually giving full traverse for the gun.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Many SPs cannot fire without deploying stabilizers or spades, sometimes hydraulic.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] A few SPs are designed so that the recoil forces of the gun are transferred directly onto the ground through a baseplate.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] A few towed guns have been given limited self-propulsion by means of an auxiliary engine.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Two other forms of tactical propulsion were used in the first half of the 20th century: Railways or transporting the equipment by road, as two or three separate loads, with disassembly and re-assembly at the beginning and end of the journey.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Railway artillery took two forms, railway mountings for heavy and super-heavy guns and howitzers and armored trains as "fighting vehicles" armed with light artillery in a direct fire role.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Disassembled transport was also used with heavy and super heavy weapons and lasted into the 1950s.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] A third form of artillery typing is to classify it as "light", "medium", "heavy" and various other terms.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] It appears to have been introduced in World War I, which spawned a very wide array of artillery in all sorts of sizes so a simple categorical system was needed.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Some armies defined these categories by bands of calibers.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p02] Different bands were used for different types of weapons—field guns, mortars, anti-aircraft guns and coastal guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Artillery is used in a variety of roles depending on its type and caliber.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The general role of artillery is to provide *fire support*—"the application of fire, coordinated with the manoeuvre of forces to destroy, *neutralize* or *suppress* the enemy".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] This NATO definition makes artillery a supporting arm although not all NATO armies agree with this logic.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Unlike rocket artillery, guns, howitzers, and mortars are well-suited for providing *close supporting fire*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] However, they are all suitable for providing *deep supporting fire* although the limited range of many mortars tends to exclude them from the role.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Their control arrangements and limited range also mean that mortars are most suited to *direct supporting fire*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Guns are used either for this or *general supporting fire* while rockets are mostly used for the latter.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] However, lighter rockets may be used for direct fire support.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] These rules of thumb apply to NATO armies.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Modern mortars, because of their lighter weight and simpler, more transportable design, are usually an integral part of infantry and, in some armies, armour units.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] This means they generally do not have to *concentrate* their fire so their shorter range is not a disadvantage.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Some armies also consider infantry operated mortars to be more responsive than artillery, but this is a function of the control arrangements and not the case in all armies.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] However, mortars have always been used by artillery units and remain with them in many armies, including a few in NATO.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] In NATO armies artillery is usually assigned a tactical mission that establishes its relationship and responsibilities to the formation or units it is assigned to.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] It seems that not all NATO nations use the terms and outside NATO others are probably used.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The standard terms are: *direct support*, *general support*, *general support reinforcing* and *reinforcing*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] These tactical missions are in the context of the command authority: *operational command*, *operational control*, *tactical command* or *tactical control*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] In NATO direct support generally means that the directly supporting artillery unit provides observers and liaison to the manoeuvre troops being supported, typically an artillery battalion or equivalent is assigned to a brigade and its batteries to the brigade's battalions.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] However, some armies achieve this by placing the assigned artillery units under command of the directly supported formation.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Nevertheless, the batteries' fire can be *concentrated* onto a single target, as can the fire of units in range and with the other tactical missions.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] There are several dimensions to this subject.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The first is the notion that fire may be against an *opportunity* target or may be *arranged*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] If it is the latter it may be either *on-call* or *scheduled*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Arranged targets may be part of a *fire plan*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Fire may be either *observed* or *unobserved*, if the former it may be *adjusted*, if the latter then it has to be *predicted*.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Observation of adjusted fire may be directly by a forward observer or indirectly via some other *target acquisition* system.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] These purposes have existed for most of the 20th century, although their definitions have evolved and will continue to do so, lack of *suppression* in *counterbattery* is an omission.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The tactical purposes also include various "mission verbs", a rapidly expanding subject with the modern concept of "effects based operations".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The *targeting* process is the key aspect of tactical fire control.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Depending on the circumstances and national procedures it may all be undertaken in one place or may be distributed.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] In armies practicing control from the front, most of the process may be undertaken by a forward observer or other target acquirer.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] This is particularly the case for a smaller target requiring only a few fire units.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The extent to which the process is formal or informal and makes use of computer based systems, documented norms or experience and judgement also varies widely armies and other circumstances.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Surprise may be essential or irrelevant.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] It depends on what effects are required and whether or not the target is likely to move or quickly improve its protective posture.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Airburst munitions significantly increase the relative risk for lying men, etc.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Historically most casualties occur in the first 10–15 seconds of fire, i.e. the time needed to react and improve protective posture, however, this is less relevant if airburst is used.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Modern counter-battery fire developed in World War I, with the objective of defeating the enemy's artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Typically such fire was used to suppress enemy batteries when they were or were about to interfere with the activities of friendly forces (such as to prevent enemy defensive artillery fire against an impending attack) or to systematically destroy enemy guns.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] In World War I the latter required air observation.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The first indirect counter-battery fire was in May 1900 by an observer in a balloon.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Enemy artillery can be detected in two ways, either by direct observation of the guns from the air or by ground observers (including specialist reconnaissance), or from their firing signatures.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Once hostile batteries have been detected they may be engaged immediately by friendly artillery or later at an optimum time, depending on the tactical situation and the counter-battery policy.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] In some situations the task is to locate all active enemy batteries for attack using a counter-battery fire at the appropriate moment in accordance with a plan developed by artillery intelligence staff.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] In other situations counter-battery fire may occur whenever a battery is located with sufficient accuracy.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Modern counter-battery target acquisition uses unmanned aircraft, counter-battery radar, ground reconnaissance and sound-ranging.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Counter-battery fire may be adjusted by some of the systems, for example the operator of an unmanned aircraft can 'follow' a battery if it moves.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Defensive measures by batteries include frequently changing position or constructing defensive earthworks, the tunnels used by North Korea being an extreme example.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Counter-measures include air defence against aircraft and attacking counter-battery radars physically and electronically.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] A technique called time on target (TOT) was developed by the British Army in North Africa at the end of 1941 and early 1942 particularly for counter-battery fire and other concentrations, it proved very popular.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] It relied on BBC time signals to enable officers to synchronize their watches to the second because this avoided the need to use military radio networks and the possibility of losing surprise, and the need for field telephone networks in the desert.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] With this technique the time of flight from each fire unit (battery or troop) to the target is taken from the range or firing tables, or the computer and each engaging fire unit subtracts its time of flight from the TOT to determine the time to fire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] An executive order to fire is given to all guns in the fire unit at the correct moment to fire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] When each fire unit fires their rounds at their individual firing time all the opening rounds will reach the target area almost simultaneously.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] This is especially effective when combined with techniques that allow fires for effect to be made without preliminary adjusting fires.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Multiple round simultaneous impact (MRSI) is a modern version of the earlier time on target concept.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] MRSI is when a single gun fires multiple shells so all arrive at the same target simultaneously.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] This is possible because there is more than one trajectory for a round to fly to any given target.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Typically one is below 45 degrees from horizontal and the other is above it, and by using different sized propellant charges with each shell, it is possible to utilize more than two trajectories.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Because the higher trajectories cause the shells to arc higher into the air, they take longer to reach the target.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] If shells are fired on higher trajectories for initial volleys (starting with the shell with the most propellant and working down) and later volleys are fired on the lower trajectories, with the correct timing the shells will all arrive at the same target simultaneously.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] This is useful because many more shells can land on the target with no warning.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] With traditional methods of firing, the target area may have time (however long it takes to reload and re-fire the guns) to take cover between volleys.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] However, guns capable of burst fire can deliver multiple rounds in a few seconds if they use the same firing data for each, and if guns in more than one location are firing on one target they can use Time on Target procedures so that all their shells arrive at the same time and target.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The first is guns with a high rate of fire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The second is the ability to use different sized propellant charges.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Third is a fire control computer that has the ability to compute MRSI volleys and the capability to produce firing data, sent to each gun, and then presented to the gun commander in the correct order.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The number of rounds that can be delivered in MRSI depends primarily on the range to the target and the rate of fire.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] To allow the most shells to reach the target, the target has to be in range of the lowest propellant charge.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The Archer project (developed by BAE-Systems Bofors in Sweden) is a 155 mm howitzer on a wheeled chassis which is claimed to be able to deliver up to six shells on target simultaneously from the same gun.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The 120 mm twin barrel AMOS mortar system, joint developed by Hägglunds (Sweden) and Patria (Finland), is capable of 7 + 7 shells MRSI.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The United States Crusader program (now cancelled) was slated to have MRSI capability.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] It is unclear how many fire control computers have the necessary capabilities.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Two-round MRSI firings were a popular artillery demonstration in the 1960s, where well trained detachments could show off their skills for spectators.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The destructiveness of artillery bombardments can be enhanced when some or all of the shells are set for airburst, meaning that they explode in the air above the target instead of upon impact.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] This can be accomplished either through time fuzes or proximity fuzes.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Time fuzes use a precise timer to detonate the shell after a preset delay.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] This technique is tricky and slight variations in the functioning of the fuze can cause it to explode too high and be ineffective, or to strike the ground instead of exploding above it.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Since December 1944 (Battle of the Bulge), proximity fuzed artillery shells have been available that take the guesswork out of this process.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] These employ a miniature, low powered radar transmitter in the fuze to detect the ground and explode them at a predetermined height above it.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The return of the weak radar signal completes an electrical circuit in the fuze which explodes the shell.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] The proximity fuze itself was developed by the British to increase the effectiveness of anti-aircraft warfare.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] This is a very effective tactic against infantry and light vehicles, because it scatters the fragmentation of the shell over a larger area and prevents it from being blocked by terrain or entrenchments that do not include some form of robust overhead cover.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/artillery-p03] Numerous war memorials around the world incorporate an artillery piece that was used in the war or battle commemorated.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] Many attempts had been made at developing breech-loading cannons, but had only partial success sealing of the breech.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] When fired, hot gases and burning gunpowder could escape, losing power and potentially burning the operating crew.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] Rifles, with smaller loads and thus less stress, were able to use rubber in O-rings as on the Chassepot rifle.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] The same principle of breech sealing for cannons was not as easy to develop.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] Several materials were able to hold the pressure and heat of cannon fire, but did not expand like rubber, thereby failing to provide a tight seal.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] The most successful of those designs was the Broadwell ring invented by American engineer Lewis Wells Broadwell (who worked as a sales agent for the Gatling Gun Company in Europe) in the early 1860s and widely applied (without a license) by the Krupp company on Krupp gun breech-loaders.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] In 1872, de Bange designed the *de Bange system*, a new type of obturating ring for breech-loading artillery pieces.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] His system used the same general principle devised by Andrew Hotchkiss ca.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] When the gun fired the nose was driven rearward, compressing the asbestos pad and squeezing it so it expanded outward to seal the breech.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] The French referred to the shape of the breech's nose as "mushroom like".
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] The action was controlled by a handle, which normally was mounted vertically on the right side of the breech.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] When lifted, the handle operated a cam that forced the breech to rotate counter-clockwise, unlocking the interrupted thread.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] The breech was then pulled rearward with the same handle, sliding on a ring-shaped holder.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] The breech holder was hinged on one side, normally the left, so when the breech block was slid all the way to the rear it could be rotated out of the way for loading.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] The de Bange system was widely adopted, including by the United States Navy and the British Royal Navy.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] The technique developed by de Bange is still in use.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] The only major improvement to the original de Bange system was the introduction of the stepped screw in the Welin breech block of 1889, which greatly increased the load-bearing surface of the breech, allowing it to be made shorter, simpler, more secure, and faster to operate.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] Other block mechanisms are also used but the de Bange obturator remains widespread.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] In 1873, de Bange became Director of the "Atelier-de-précision" in the Central Depot in Paris (Paris arsenal's precision workshop), in order to redesign French light and heavy artillery.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] Several of these weapons were used during the colonial wars of the end of the 19th century, during the First World War and also sometimes during the Second World War.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] As with other cannons, the de Bange cannons had the disadvantage of being slow to fire, as they were affected by recoil, and thus had to be re-aimed after every shot.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] This inconvenience would be solved with the appearance of the famous Canon de 75, that had a hydro-pneumatic recoil mechanism, which kept the gun's trail and wheels perfectly still during the firing sequence.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] However, there were two howitzers the Obusier de 120 mm C modèle 1890 and Obusier de 155 mm C modèle 1890 with de Bange breeches and recoil mechanisms designed by Captain Louis Henry Auguste Baquet.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] From 1882 to 1889, de Bange was Director of the Cail Manufacturing Corporation (*Société Anonyme des Anciens Etablissements Cail*), the forerunner of the *Société française de constructions mécaniques*, where he worked on weapon design and trade, selling guns to such countries as Serbia.
[src:charles-ragon-de-bange/charles-ragon-de-bange] A street is named after him (*Rue du Colonel de Bange*) in the city of Versailles.
